        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Dornette</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Folks, this is all about demanding some kind of consistency from Verant. The technology exists for the pet to be able to zone with his master. There is no compelling reason for our pets not to zone as we do. Not one person here has presented one valid reason that *all* pet classes should not be able to have their pets zone.</P><P>Yes we pay a great price to be able to use pets but I would then pose the question: why should players then be able to zone with full buffs on? For example, the paladin uses his mana to buff himself and that gives him an advantage. The pet class uses his mana to summon a pet. So here we have 2 different classes using mana in different ways yet to the same end goal--to gain an advantage against an NPC. The difference is that the Paladin can zone with his mana (the buff) while the pet class can't zone with his mana (the pet).  Perhaps then all classes should be stripped of their buffs *each* time they zone. Sound fair???</P><P>Well this is exactly what you are asking pet classes to do. You are asking them expend huge amounts of mana each time they zone to get a pet. A pet class caster is not complete without their pet and can't exist very long without one. We are designed to be very weak without a pet. No other class has to pay a penalty for the right to zone the way pet classes do. None. </P><P>Pet classes other than Beastlords are the only classes that are penalized for the artificial concept of having to "zone". Just think about that for a minute and ask yourself if that is fair and maybe other classes should pay a price and lose their part of their abilities and a huge chunk of their mana for the priviledge of zoning.</P><P>Let me address some concerns:</P><P>-wiz familiars are not pets</P><P>Yeah, we know this. The point is that pets and familiars--entities under the control of the master who summoned them can currently zone. The technology exists. Let's apply it fairly across the board to all pet classes.</P><P>-beastlords have to buff their pets upon zoning this equates to summoning a pet</P><P>I disagree. At least the Beastlord pet can tank for the master if the Beastlord zones into an unfriendly zone. In fact lets have the Beastlord pets zone will full buffs...it's only fair.</P><P>The Beastlord can buff his pet while the pet is tanking. The necromancer has to wait a good 11 seconds at least for the pet to be case *after* zoning. That is a huge difference.</P><P>Another glaring difference is the mana cost of a Beastlord pet compared to a 59 spectre pet. The Beastlord warder costs 750 mana total and the spectre costs 900 mana total. The Beastlord at least gets a mana less pet to start off with when they zone.</P><P>-Dire Charm pets</P><P>Dire Charm mobs are part of the zone NPC table. They are not pets in the traditional sense. We are talking about user summoned pets, not charmed pets. Nobody is asking for DC pets to be able to zone. It does not make any sense at all and is a poor excuse to discount the real argument there that *all* summoned pets should be able to zone with their masters.</P><P>-Zones are an integral part of the game. This would be overpowering.</P><P>Of course they are, but what does this have to do with the ability to have the pet you summoned (with your hard earned mana and periodot) to be able to zone with you? Players can zone with full buffs on...why not pets?</P><P>Overpowering? Says who? Why is it not overpowering for a Beastlord to zone with his pet but yet it's somehow overpowering for a necromancer to do so?</P><P>-No point whining about it</P><P>Nobody is "whining". This is a valid argument and deserves serious consideration. I recall this same label of "whiner" was applied to all of us who lobbyed hard for improvements to the spectre pet and pet resists. These doubters said it would never happen and that it would be "overpowering". Well look what happens when necromancers come together and present logical argument and stick to their guns--Verant finally saw the light and fixed pets.</P><P>-Bril said it all, it won't happen anyway</P><P>Yeah just like our spectre pet would never get upgraded. Just like pets won't ever get indifferent con. Just like pets won't ever not attacked a mezzed mob. Just like pts won't ever get good resists. Comments like the above are typical comments of a defeatist attitude. Well it certainly won't happen if we don't raise our voices and get this inconsistency fixed.</P><P>The original poster of this topic deserves some credit for daring to question a Verant sacred cow of pets not being able to zone. Sometimes I'm a little ashamed to be a necromancer when I read how unsupportive many fellow necromancers are some of us who are trying to elevate the cause of this class. Some of the attitudes here are akin to driving through some backwoods sleepy town where the people are all narrow-minded and refuse to embrace any kind of change. If we are to ever continue to remain viable as class we need to speak out on issues that affect us. These recent changes by Verant just prove that what we talk about on these boards can make a real difference.</P><P></P><P><BR>Dornette<BR>60 necromancer<BR>The Nameless</P><P>Edited by - Dornette on 07/24/2002  05:34:56</font></td>
